# Canonical crash / rapid-restart policy — the SINGLE source shared by BOTH
# bridge restart guards, so tuning one layer can never silently diverge from the
# other (#445). Shell-sourceable (KEY=VALUE) by start.sh's supervisor AND parsed
# by telegram_bot.core.crash_policy, which the in-process guard reads.
#
# Two DELIBERATELY NESTED restart layers, each owning a distinct concern:
#
#   1. In-process guard  (core/bot_lifecycle.py): rebuilds the Telegram polling
#      transport WITHOUT exiting the process, so a transient network blip never
#      tears down in-flight agent turns (#411). A rebuilt polling loop that dies
#      again within CCC_INPROCESS_MIN_UPTIME_SECONDS counts as rapid; after
#      CCC_MAX_RAPID_CRASHES in a row it gives up by raising a non-zero
#      SystemExit — deliberately escalating to layer 2.
#
#   2. Process supervisor (start.sh run_daemon_supervisor): respawns the whole
#      process. A process that dies within CCC_PROCESS_CRASH_WINDOW_SECONDS
#      counts as rapid; after CCC_MAX_RAPID_CRASHES it stops respawning.
#
# By design, layer 1's give-up (non-zero exit) is observed by layer 2 as exactly
# ONE process crash: the in-process layer absorbs transient churn without paying
# a full process restart, and the supervisor bounds the process lifetime. The
# two windows differ on purpose — in-process recovery reacts faster (30s) than
# the heavier process respawn window (60s). The shared CCC_MAX_RAPID_CRASHES
# keeps both layers' "how many strikes" identical.
CCC_MAX_RAPID_CRASHES=5
CCC_PROCESS_CRASH_WINDOW_SECONDS=60
CCC_INPROCESS_MIN_UPTIME_SECONDS=30
CCC_RESTART_DELAY_BASE_SECONDS=3
CCC_RESTART_DELAY_MAX_SECONDS=30
